<h2>%%ReferenceStyle%%Journal article, multiple articles by same author</h2>
<hr>
<strong>WORKS CITED</strong>
<br><br>
Add a &#8216;Works Cited&#8217; entry at the end of your essay citing all sources used in the body of your writing.
<br><br>
<strong>Format</strong>
<br>
<blockquote>
	<div class="ref-hang-indent">
		Author&#8217;s name. &#34;Title of Article.&#34; <em>Name of Journal</em>, 
		volume, issue, year of publication, page numbers.
	</div>
	<div class="ref-hang-indent">
		&#45;&nbsp;&#45;&nbsp;&#45;. &#34;Title of article.&#34; <em>Name of Journal</em>, 
		volume, issue, year of publication, page numbers.
	</div>
</blockquote>
<br>
Give the author&#8217;s name in the first entry only. After that use three hyphens, followed by a full stop. Multiple works by the same author are listed alphabetically by title.
<br><br>
References with the same first author and a different second or third author are listed alphabetically by name.
<br><br>
<strong>Example</strong>
<br>
<blockquote>
	<div class="ref-hang-indent">
		<span class="hover" title="Author&#8217;s name">Smith, Andrew</span>. 
		&#34;<span class="hover" title="Title of Article">Leading by Example</span>.&#34; 
		<em><span class="hover" title="Name of Journal">Management Research International</span></em>,
		<span class="hover" title="volume">vol. 3</span>, <span class="hover" title="issue">no. 4</span>,
		<span class="hover" title="year of publication">2056</span>,
		<span class="hover" title="page numbers">pp. 45&#45;48</span>.
	</div>
	<div class="ref-hang-indent">
		&#45;&nbsp;&#45;&nbsp;&#45;. &#34;Teaming with Wildlife: Promoting Team Development 
		through Volunteer Service at Auckland Zoo.&#34;
		<em>New Zealand Business Review</em>, vol. 17, no. 4, 2050, pp. 230-40. 
	</div>
	<div class="ref-hang-indent">
		Smith, Andrew, and Bev Brown. &#34;Learning Through Teaching.&#34; 
		<em>Teaching and Learning in Higher Education</em>, vol. 3, no. 4, 2056, pp. 45-48. 
	</div>
</blockquote>
